DSSS2022 Machine Learning in R: Task List 01

Goran S. Milovanovic, DataKolektiv

Data visualization in ggplot2

We will exercise our ggplot2 skills a bit here!

You may rely on R for Data Science, chapter 2 Data visualization to complete this exercise.

ggplot2 in tidyverse

Load tidyverse:

library(tidyverse)

The dataset

We will use the same dataset as we have used in out Task List 1 for dplyr exercises: Our World in Data - COVID-19 Data Explorer:

  • Dataset GitHub repository
  • Dataset CSV file

based on:

Mathieu, E., Ritchie, H., Ortiz-Ospina, E. et al.A global database of COVID-19 vaccinations. Nat Hum Behav (2021). https://doi.org/10.1038/s41562-021-01122-8.

We can access the CSV file directly from Rs read.csv(), as we have demonstrated in the classroom on Saturday, June 4:

file_url <- "https://covid.ourworldindata.org/data/owid-covid-data.csv"
data_set <- read.csv(file_url, 
                     header = TRUE,
                     check.names = FALSE,
                     stringsAsFactors = FALSE)
head(data_set)

Similarly as in our Task List 01, we need to remove everything where the iso_code begins with ^OWID_:

data_set <- data_set %>% 
  filter(!str_detect(iso_code, "^OWID_"))

Task 0.

Essentially, you do nothing in Task 0: just follow me as I add successive layers to a simple ggplot2 visualization. I would like to visualize the number of cases per year. First I need a data.frame for this visualization:

data_set$year <- substr(data_set$date, 1, 4)
plot_frame <- data_set %>% 
  select(new_cases, year) %>% 
  group_by(year) %>% 
  summarise(cases = sum(new_cases, na.rm = TRUE))
print(plot_frame)

Lets define the visualization mapping in aes() and plot nothing, for the beginning:

ggplot(data = plot_frame, 
       aes(x = year, y = cases))

Ok: ggplot2 recognizes my variables and their scales, but plots nothing. I need to add some geoms there for plot to materialize:

ggplot(data = plot_frame, 
       aes(x = year, y = cases)) + 
  geom_point(size = 1.5, color = "darkred") + 
  geom_path(group = 1, size = .5, color = "darkred")

I could have added a different geom:

ggplot(data = plot_frame, 
       aes(x = year, y = cases)) + 
  geom_bar(width = .5, stat = "identity", fill = "darkred", color = "black")

Now, what about total_cases per month and per year? I need a new plot_frame for this:

data_set$year <- substr(data_set$date, 1, 4)
data_set$month <- as.character(substr(data_set$date, 6, 7))
plot_frame <- data_set %>% 
  select(total_cases, year, month) %>% 
  group_by(year, month) %>% 
  summarise(cases = sum(total_cases, na.rm = TRUE))
print(plot_frame)

Now:

ggplot(data = plot_frame, 
       aes(x = month, 
           y = cases,
           fill = year, 
           color = year)) + 
  geom_bar(width = .5,
           stat = "identity", 
           position = position_dodge(width = 0.5))

Or I can do facet_wrap:

ggplot(data = plot_frame, 
       aes(x = month, 
           y = cases,
           fill = year, 
           color = year)) + 
  geom_bar(width = .5,
           stat = "identity") + 
  facet_wrap(~year, nrow = 3)

Now I can begin using theme() in order to style my chart.

ggplot(data = plot_frame, 
       aes(x = month, 
           y = cases,
           fill = year, 
           color = year)) + 
  geom_bar(width = .5,
           stat = "identity") + 
  facet_wrap(~year, nrow = 3) + 
  theme_bw() + 
  theme(legend.position = "top")

Even better:

ggplot(data = plot_frame, 
       aes(x = month, 
           y = cases,
           fill = year, 
           color = year)) + 
  geom_bar(width = .5,
           stat = "identity") + 
  facet_wrap(~year, nrow = 3) + 
  theme_bw() + 
  theme(legend.position = "top") + 
  theme(strip.background = element_rect(fill = "white", color = "white")) + 
  theme(panel.border = element_blank())

If you want to avoid using the scientific notation on a scale (look at our y-axis), you can use the scales library:

# install.packages('scales')
library(scales)
ggplot(data = plot_frame, 
       aes(x = month, 
           y = cases,
           fill = year, 
           color = year)) + 
  geom_bar(width = .5,
           stat = "identity") + 
  facet_wrap(~year, nrow = 3) + 
  scale_y_continuous(labels = comma) + 
  theme_bw() + 
  theme(legend.position = "top") + 
  theme(strip.background = element_rect(fill = "white", color = "white")) + 
  theme(panel.border = element_blank())

Lets now produce a scatter plot of the - mean number of new_cases per day, per country - and the countrys population (taking the latest available data).

Population first:

population_set <- data_set %>% 
  select(location, date, population) %>% 
  arrange(location, date) %>% 
  group_by(location) %>% 
  slice_tail()
population_set

Now, the average number of total_cases per country:

cases_set <- data_set %>% 
  select(location, new_cases) %>% 
  group_by(location) %>% 
  summarise(mean_cases_per_day = mean(new_cases, na.rm = TRUE))
cases_set

Now I need to join cases_set to population_set by locations; if you are interested to learn about relational structures and join operations in dplyr in R, go read section 13 Relational data in R for Data Science.

plot_frame <- left_join(population_set, 
                        cases_set,
                        by = "location")
plot_frame

Here goes our scatter plot:

ggplot(data = plot_frame, 
       aes(x = population, y = mean_cases_per_day)) + 
  geom_point(size = 1, color = "darkred") + 
  geom_point(size = .75, color = "white") + 
  scale_y_continuous(labels = comma) + 
  scale_x_continuous(labels = comma) + 
  theme_bw() + 
  theme(panel.border = element_blank())

Maybe using log() scales?

ggplot(data = plot_frame, 
       aes(x = log(population), 
           y = log(mean_cases_per_day))) + 
  geom_point(size = 1, color = "darkred") + 
  geom_point(size = .75, color = "white") + 
  scale_y_continuous(labels = comma) + 
  scale_x_continuous(labels = comma) + 
  theme_bw() + 
  theme(panel.border = element_blank())

We can place the best fitting linear model on the chart by geom_smooth(method="lm):

ggplot(data = plot_frame, 
       aes(x = log(population), 
           y = log(mean_cases_per_day))) + 
  geom_smooth(size = .25, method = "lm") + 
  geom_point(size = 1, color = "darkred") + 
  geom_point(size = .75, color = "white") + 
  scale_y_continuous(labels = comma) + 
  scale_x_continuous(labels = comma) + 
  theme_bw() + 
  theme(panel.border = element_blank())
